This paper discusses the connectivity properties of random key graphs, which are commonly used in wireless sensor networks. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also discusses the use of random key graphs in various domains, including clustering and classification analysis, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), as well as cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) due to its relevance to social networks. The paper also discusses the security aspects of random key graphs, which could place it in the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents results in the form of zero-one laws, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.IT (Information Theory).
